    en: "When a municipality adopts a new zoning ordinance or amends an existing one, uses and structures that existed lawfully before the change often become 'legal nonconforming' — prohibited by the new rules but protected as grandfathered. Town Law 267-b (with parallel provisions in Village Law 7-712-b and General City Law 81-a) recognizes the right to continue a nonconforming use, but also permits reasonable limits on expansion, abandonment, and reconstruction. Abandonment for a specified period (often 12 to 24 months) typically terminates the nonconforming right. A nonconforming use cannot ordinarily be enlarged, substantially altered, or changed to a different nonconforming use without a variance."
